The most elegant version of what you’re doing is this:

Treat all those prefixes as a single layered “voice stack,” where only the outermost layer determines the grammatical object. Everything inside is demoted relative to it.

That gives you a clean, deterministic system with no “competing objects” problem.


** 1. Prefixes form a hierarchy (outer > inner)
Core rule (the elegant solution)

Verbal prefixes are not independent operators. They are ordered layers of grammatical prominence.

So:

OUT- DAT- V

is not “two operations acting equally,” but:

OUT- (dominant frame) wrapping DAT- (subordinate frame) wrapping the verb

** 2. Only the outermost prefix controls the Accusative
The outermost prefix determines what becomes the core object
Everything else is forced into oblique or non-core status

** 3. Inner prefixes become semantic, not structural

They still matter—but only in meaning, not syntax.

** What this fixes immediately

No more “three objects competing.”

Instead:

one syntactic winner (outer layer)
one semantic structure underneath
everything else demoted predictably


** Apply it to your system

Let’s define roles:

OUT- = comparative frame (introduces standard of comparison)
DAT- = recipient promotion frame
Base verb = theme

** Case 1: DAT- outside OUT-

DAT- OUT- give money church Tam

Interpretation:

Outer frame = DAT-
→ church becomes Accusative (core object)

Inner OUT- = comparison
→ Tam becomes oblique standard

Result:

Kak gave the church money, more than Tam did.

** Case 2: OUT- outside DAT-

OUT- DAT- give money church Tam

Interpretation:

Outer frame = OUT-
→ Tam becomes Accusative (comparison target promoted)

Inner DAT-
→ church becomes dative (non-core recipient)

Result:

Kak outdid Tam in giving money to the church.

** Case 3: No stacking (base usage)

DAT- give money church

→ church = Accusative
→ simple benefactive reading

** Why this is elegant

Because it gives you:

1. Determinism

No ambiguity about “which object wins.”

2. Linear processing

You read prefixes left-to-right (or right-to-left, but consistent), and the structure resolves automatically.

3. No extra cases needed

You don’t need:

comparative case
second accusative
special “standard of comparison” case

Everything is handled by layering.

** The conceptual payoff (important for your design)

What you’ve actually created is:

A templatic voice system, not a case system expansion.

Meaning:

syntax is controlled by frames
case is just the surface realization of frame choice
argument roles are reassigned structurally, not stored as labels

One clean formulation you could put in your grammar

You could literally write:

Verbal prefixes are ordered operators forming a hierarchical voice stack.
The outermost operator determines the clause’s primary object.
All subordinate operators are interpreted within its domain but do not affect core case assignment.

If you want to push it one step further

You could later refine it into:

fixed prefix order (OUT- always outermost or innermost)
or semantic precedence rules (e.g., comparison > recipient)
or even allow “neutral stacking” where meaning is purely compositional
